[5] Israel (Tel Aviv): wild birds, park
Date: Thu 5 Jan 2017
Source: Israel Hayom daily [in Hebrew, trans. Mod.AS, summ., edited]
http://www.israelhayom.co.il/article/441691


Bird flu was discovered this morning [Thu 5 Jan 2017] in the Ramat-Gan National Park following the deaths of 2 ducks and a goose in the park. Professional consultation held between the relevant bodies in the Ministry of Agriculture, Ministry of Health, the NPA [National reserves and parks Authority], the Ramat Gan National Park, and the Ramat Gan municipality, it was agreed that the type being diagnosed is not dangerous to humans.

The dead birds were sent to the diagnostic laboratory at the Veterinary Institute in Beit Dagan and policy coordinated with the Ministries of Health and Agriculture. Park operations will continue as usual, while also continuing to follow the birds in the park. The public can continue to visit the national park as usual.

--
Communicated by
Nati Elkin
<nati@poultrymed.com>

[Most likely the event above is caused by HPAI H5N8, becoming Israel's outbreak no. 20, since the start of the event in November 2016. All 20 outbreaks are presented on the interactive map at http://tinyurl.com/z8zzdcg (for the details of each outbreak, left-click on its sign).

HPAI H5N8 virus detection continues to be reported in previously affected countries in Europe, in Israel, and possibly in India. In particular, outbreaks in poultry have been reported in Germany, Sweden, Romania, Poland, Hungary, France, Bulgaria, and Israel.

Since its detection in early June 2016 in wild birds in Tyva (Russian Federation/RUS), H5N8 HPAI has been spreading globally probably mainly along wild birds' migratory routes. Since mid-October [2016] it was reported in several species of wild or domestic birds in India, in 18 countries in Europe (Hungary, Poland, Croatia, Austria, Germany, Switzerland, the Netherlands, Denmark, Sweden, RUS, Finland, Romania, France, Serbia, Ukraine, UK, Bulgaria, and Greece) and most probably also the Czech Republic, in 3 countries in Africa (Egypt, Tunisia, and Nigeria), and in Iran and Israel. Its circulation in the Middle and Near East may not be limited to the latter 2 countries; surveillance deserves to be intensified in other countries situated along the Eurasian-African migratory birds flyways. - Mod.AS

A map showing the migratory bird flyways can be seen at http://www.fao.org/avianflu/en/wildlife/img/flyways.gif. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
